units.text:
The problem with  `var`  is function scope instead of block scope:
text


```
if(true){
  var leaked="oops"
}
console.log(leaked)// "oops" - var escaped!

if(true){
  let contained="safe"
}
console.log(contained)// Error - let stayed inside

```

With  `var`,variables leak out of blocks unexpectedly. This causes subtle bugs.  `let`  keeps variables where you expect them.

The  `typeof null==="object"`  bug exists because early JavaScript represented  `null`  with the same bit pattern as objects. Fixing it would break existing code,so it remains.
To check for  `null`,use strict equality:
text


```
if(value===null){
  // Handle null
}

```

Similarly,to distinguish arrays from objects,use  `Array.isArray(value)`  instead of  `typeof` .

Loose equality causes real bugs:
text


```
let input="0"  // User typed "0"

if(input==false){
  // This runs! "0"==false is true
  console.log("No input provided")}

```

With  `===`,this bug is obvious:
text


```
if(input===false){
  // This doesn't run
  // "0" is a string,false is a boolean
}

```

Teams often enforce  `===`  with linter rules. It's one of the easiest ways to prevent bugs.

Write code that validates variable types:
text


```
function validateUser(name,age,active){
  if(typeof name !=="string"){
    console.log("Name must be a string")
return false
  }
  if(typeof age !=="number" || Number.isNaN(age)){
    console.log("Age must be a number")
return false
  }
  if(typeof active !=="boolean"){
    console.log("Active must be a boolean")
return false
  }
  return true
}

```

Type validation prevents bugs when working with user input or API data.

Use  `else`  to run code when the condition is false:
text


```
let age=15

if(age >=18){
  console.log("Adult")} else {
  console.log("Minor")}

```

Exactly one branch runs. If the condition is true,the first block runs. If false,the else block runs. This handles the "otherwise" case.

Chain multiple conditions with  `else if` :
text


```
let score=85

if(score >=90){
  console.log("A")} else if(score >=80){
  console.log("B")} else if(score >=70){
  console.log("C")} else {
  console.log("F")}

```

Conditions are checked top to bottom. The first true condition runs,and the rest are skipped. Order matters when ranges overlap.

Check more specific conditions first:
text


```
// WRONG: score >=70 is true for 85
if(score >=70){
  console.log("C")} else if(score >=80){
  console.log("B")// Never reached!
}

// RIGHT: check higher scores first
if(score >=80){
  console.log("B")} else if(score >=70){
  console.log("C")}

```

When conditions overlap,the first matching one wins. Structure your conditions from most specific to least specific.

You can nest if statements inside each other:
text


```
let age=25
let hasTicket=true

if(age >=18){
  if(hasTicket){
    console.log("Enjoy the show")} else {
    console.log("Buy a ticket first")}
} else {
  console.log("Must be 18+")}

```

Nesting works but can get hard to read. When possible,flatten nested conditions using  `&&`  or early returns.

Instead of nesting,combine conditions:
text


```
// Nested version
if(age >=18){
  if(hasTicket){
    enter()}
}

// Flattened version
if(age >=18 && hasTicket){
  enter()}

```

Flat code is easier to read and debug. Use  `&&`  to combine conditions that must all be true. Use  `||`  for conditions where any can be true.

Guard clauses handle edge cases first and return early:
text


```
function processUser(user){
  if(!user){
    console.log("No user")return
  }
  if(!user.isActive){
    console.log("User inactive")return
  }
  // Main logic here - no nesting needed
  console.log(`Processing ${user.name}`)}

```

This pattern eliminates deep nesting. Handle invalid cases first,then write the happy path without indentation.

Use  `switch`  for exact value matching against multiple options. Use  `if-else`  for ranges or complex conditions.
text


```
// Better as switch - exact matches
switch(command){
  case "start": ...
  case "stop": ...
  case "pause": ...
}

// Better as if-else - ranges
if(score >=90){ ... }
else if(score >=80){ ... }

```

Switch is cleaner for many exact matches. If-else is more flexible for everything else.

For simple if-else that assigns a value,use the ternary operator:
text


```
// if-else version
let message
if(age >=18){
  message="Adult"
} else {
  message="Minor"
}

// Ternary version
let message=age >=18 ? "Adult" : "Minor"

```

Ternary is best for simple choices between 2 values. For complex logic or multiple conditions,stick with if-else.

Use logical operators to build complex conditions:
text


```
let age=25
let hasLicense=true
let hasInsurance=true

if(age >=18 && hasLicense && hasInsurance){
  console.log("Can drive legally")}

if(age < 16 || !hasPermission){
  console.log("Cannot drive")}

```

 `&&`  requires all conditions to be true.  `||`  requires at least one to be true. Use parentheses to group and clarify.

Parentheses group conditions:
text


```
// Is this person eligible?
let isEligible=(age >=18 && isCitizen)|| hasSpecialPermit

// Can access this resource?
let canAccess=isAdmin ||(isUser && hasPermission)
```

Without parentheses,`&&`  has higher precedence than  `||` . Be explicit with parentheses to show your intent clearly:
text


```
// Ambiguous
a || b && c

// Clear
a ||(b && c)(a || b)&& c

```

Build a grade calculator:
text


```
let score=85
let grade

if(score >=90){
  grade="A"
} else if(score >=80){
  grade="B"
} else if(score >=70){
  grade="C"
} else if(score >=60){
  grade="D"
} else {
  grade="F"
}

console.log(`Score: ${score},Grade: ${grade}`)
```

Try different scores. Notice how exactly one branch runs.

Build login validation:
text


```
let username="alice"
let password="secret123"
let isLocked=false
let attempts=2

if(isLocked){
  console.log("Account locked")} else if(!username || !password){
  console.log("Enter username and password")} else if(attempts >=3){
  console.log("Too many attempts")} else if(username==="alice" && password==="secret123"){
  console.log("Login successful")} else {
  console.log("Invalid credentials")}

```

A  `while`  loop runs as long as its condition is true:
text


```
let count=0

while(count < 5){
  console.log(count)count++}
// Prints: 0,1,2,3,4

```

The condition is checked before each iteration. If it starts false,the loop body never runs. Always ensure something inside the loop eventually makes the condition false.

If the condition never becomes false,the loop runs forever:
text


```
// DON'T RUN THIS - infinite loop!
while(true){
  console.log("Forever")}

```

Infinite loops freeze your program. They happen when you forget to update the condition variable:
text


```
let i=0
while(i < 5){
  console.log(i)// Forgot i++! Loop runs forever
}

```

Always verify your loop has an exit path.

Count down by starting high and decrementing:
text


```
for(let i=5; i > 0; i--){
  console.log(i)}
// Prints: 5,4,3,2,1

```

Or use different step sizes:
text


```
for(let i=0; i < 10; i+=2){
  console.log(i)}
// Prints: 0,2,4,6,8

```

The update expression can be any change that eventually makes the condition false.

The  `for...of`  loop iterates over values in arrays and strings:
text


```
let colors=["red","green","blue"]

for(let color of colors){
  console.log(color)}
// Prints: red,green,blue

let word="hello"
for(let char of word){
  console.log(char)}
// Prints: h,e,l,l,o

```

Use  `for...of`  when you need values,not indices. It's cleaner than indexing manually.

The  `for...in`  loop iterates over object keys:
text


```
let person={ name: "Alice",age: 30 }

for(let key in person){
  console.log(key,person[key])}
// Prints: name Alice,age 30

```

Don't use  `for...in`  on arrays. It iterates indices as strings and may include inherited properties. Use  `for...of`  for arrays instead.

The  `break`  statement exits a loop immediately:
text


```
for(let i=0; i < 10; i++){
  if(i===5){
    break  // Exit when i is 5
  }
  console.log(i)}
// Prints: 0,1,2,3,4

```

Use  `break`  when you find what you're looking for and don't need to continue:
text


```
for(let item of items){
  if(item===target){
    console.log("Found!")break
  }
}

```

The  `continue`  statement skips to the next iteration:
text


```
for(let i=0; i < 5; i++){
  if(i===2){
    continue  // Skip when i is 2
  }
  console.log(i)}
// Prints: 0,1,3,4

```

Use  `continue`  to skip items that don't match your criteria:
text


```
for(let num of numbers){
  if(num < 0)continue  // Skip negatives
  console.log(num)}

```

Loops can contain other loops:
text


```
for(let i=1; i <=3; i++){
  for(let j=1; j <=3; j++){
    console.log(i,j)}
}
// Prints: 1 1,1 2,1 3,2 1,2 2,2 3,3 1,3 2,3 3

```

The inner loop completes fully for each iteration of the outer loop. With 3 outer and 3 inner iterations,you get 9 total iterations.

Regular  `break`  only exits the innermost loop. To exit outer loops,use labels:
text


```
outer: for(let i=0; i < 3; i++){
  for(let j=0; j < 3; j++){
    if(i===1 && j===1){
      break outer  // Exits both loops
    }
    console.log(i,j)}
}

```

Labels are rarely needed. Usually you can restructure code or use a function with  `return`  instead.

Collect items that match a condition:
text


```
let numbers=[1,2,3,4,5,6]
let evens=[]

for(let num of numbers){
  if(num%2===0){
    evens.push(num)}
}

console.log(evens)// [2,4,6]

```

Start with an empty array. Push items that match your criteria. Later you'll learn array methods like  `filter()`  that do this more concisely.

Print numbers 1-20. For multiples of 3 print "Fizz",for 5 print "Buzz",for both print "FizzBuzz":
text


```
for(let i=1; i <=20; i++){
  if(i%3===0 && i%5===0){
    console.log("FizzBuzz")} else if(i%3===0){
    console.log("Fizz")} else if(i%5===0){
    console.log("Buzz")} else {
    console.log(i)}
}

```

This classic interview question tests loops and conditions together.

Find the largest number in an array:
text


```
let numbers=[42,17,89,23,56]
let max=numbers[0]  // Start with first element

for(let num of numbers){
  if(num > max){
    max=num
  }
}

console.log(`Maximum: ${max}`)// 89

```

Starting with the first element(not 0)handles negative numbers correctly.

Build a number guessing game concept:
text


```
let secret=7
let guesses=[5,8,7]  // Simulated guesses
let attempts=0

for(let guess of guesses){
  attempts++if(guess===secret){
    console.log(`Correct in ${attempts} attempts!`)break
  } else if(guess < secret){
    console.log("Too low")} else {
    console.log("Too high")}
}

```

This demonstrates loops with conditions,break,and counter tracking.

Declare functions with the  `function`  keyword:
text


```
function sayHello(){
  console.log("Hello!")}

function showDate(){
  console.log(new Date())}

sayHello()// Hello!
showDate()// Current date

```

The name follows the same rules as variables: camelCase,starting with a letter. Choose descriptive names that say what the function does.

Functions can have multiple parameters:
text


```
function add(a,b){
  console.log(a+b)}

add(5,3)// 8
add(10,20)// 30

function introduce(name,age,city){
  console.log(`${name},${age},from ${city}`)}

introduce("Alice",30,"Seattle")
```

Parameters are matched by position. The first argument goes to the first parameter,second to second,and so on.

Arrow functions provide a shorter syntax:
text


```
// Traditional
const add=function(a,b){
  return a+b
}

// Arrow
const add=(a,b)=> {
  return a+b
}

// Arrow with implicit return
const add=(a,b)=> a+b

```

When the body is a single expression,you can omit braces and  `return` . The result is automatically returned.

Variables declared outside functions have global scope:
text


```
const API_URL="https://api.example.com"

function fetchData(){
  console.log(API_URL)// Accessible here
}

function sendData(){
  console.log(API_URL)// Accessible here too
}

```

Global variables are accessible from anywhere. Limit them to constants and configuration. Too many globals make code hard to reason about.

Variables declared with  `let`  and  `const`  have block scope:
text


```
function example(){
  if(true){
    let x=10
    const y=20
  }
  console.log(x)// Error: x is not defined
}

```

Block scope means variables exist only within the  `{}`  where they're declared. This includes if statements,loops,and any other blocks.

A callback is a function passed to another function:
text


```
function processData(data,callback){
  console.log("Processing...")callback(data)}

function logResult(result){
  console.log("Result:",result)}

processData(42,logResult)// Processing...
// Result: 42

```

Callbacks let you customize behavior. The receiving function decides when to call your callback.

A pure function always returns the same output for the same input and has no side effects:
text


```
// Pure - same input always gives same output
function add(a,b){
  return a+b
}

// Impure - depends on external state
let multiplier=2
function multiply(x){
  return x * multiplier  // Result depends on global
}

```

Pure functions are easier to test and debug. They're predictable because they don't depend on or modify external state.

Create these basic functions:
text


```
function square(n){
  return n * n
}

function isEven(n){
  return n%2===0
}

function max(a,b){
  return a > b ? a : b
}

console.log(square(5))// 25
console.log(isEven(4))// true
console.log(max(10,20))// 20

```

Notice how each function does one thing and returns a result.

Convert traditional functions to arrows:
text


```
// Traditional
function double(x){ return x * 2 }
function greet(name){ return "Hello,"+name }
function sum(a,b){ return a+b }

// Arrow
const double=x=> x * 2
const greet=name=> "Hello,"+name
const sum=(a,b)=> a+b

```

Practice both styles. Use arrows for short functions,traditional for longer ones.

Practice number formatting:
text


```
let price=1234.567

// Format as currency
let formatted="$"+price.toFixed(2)console.log(formatted)// "$1234.57"

// Pad order numbers
let orderId=42
let padded=String(orderId).padStart(6,"0")console.log(padded)// "000042"

// Random price between $10 and $100
let randomPrice=(Math.random()* 90+10).toFixed(2)console.log("$"+randomPrice)
```

Common text transformations:
text


```
// Title case
function toTitleCase(str){
  return str.split(" ").map(word=> word[0].toUpperCase()+word.slice(1).toLowerCase()).join(" ")}
console.log(toTitleCase("hello world"))// "Hello World"

// Slug from title
function toSlug(title){
  return title.toLowerCase().trim().replaceAll(" ","-")}
console.log(toSlug("My Blog Post"))// "my-blog-post"

```

Build a word counter:
text


```
function analyzeText(text){
  let trimmed=text.trim()let charCount=trimmed.length
  let wordCount=trimmed.split(/\s+/).filter(w=> w.length > 0).length
  let sentenceCount=trimmed.split(/[.!?]+/).filter(s=> s.length > 0).length

  return {
    characters: charCount,words: wordCount,sentences: sentenceCount
  }
}

let stats=analyzeText("Hello world. How are you?")console.log(stats)// { characters: 25,words: 5,sentences: 2 }

```

`reduce()`  can build any result:
javascript


```
let words=["hello","world"]
let sentence=words.reduce((acc,w)=> acc+" "+w)console.log(sentence)// "hello world"

// Count occurrences
let letters=["a","b","a","c","a"]
let counts=letters.reduce((acc,letter)=> {
  acc[letter]=(acc[letter] || 0)+1
  return acc
},{})console.log(counts)// { a: 3,b: 1,c: 1 }

```

Build a todo list with arrays:
javascript


```
let todos=[]

function addTodo(text){
  todos.push({ id: Date.now(),text,done: false })}

function toggleTodo(id){
  let todo=todos.find(t=> t.id===id)if(todo)todo.done=!todo.done
}

function removeTodo(id){
  let index=todos.findIndex(t=> t.id===id)if(index !==-1)todos.splice(index,1)}

function getPending(){
  return todos.filter(t=> !t.done)}

```

When variable names match property names,use shorthand:
javascript


```
let name="Alice"
let age=30

// Long form
let user1={ name: name,age: age }

// Shorthand
let user2={ name,age }

console.log(user2)// { name: "Alice",age: 30 }

```

This is common when building objects from variables. It reduces repetition and keeps code clean.

Create property names dynamically:
javascript


```
let prop="status"

let obj={
  [prop]: "active",["key"+1]: "value1"
}

console.log(obj)// { status: "active",key1: "value1" }

```

Square brackets around the key evaluate the expression. Use this for dynamic keys from variables or computations.

Objects can contain functions(methods):
javascript


```
let calculator={
  add(a,b){
    return a+b
  },subtract(a,b){
    return a - b
  }
}

console.log(calculator.add(5,3))// 8
console.log(calculator.subtract(5,3))// 2

```

The shorthand  `add(a,b){}`  is cleaner than  `add: function(a,b){}` .

Inside a method,`this`  refers to the object:
javascript


```
let user={
  name: "Alice",greet(){
    console.log("Hello,I'm "+this.name)}
}

user.greet()// "Hello,I'm Alice"

```

 `this`  lets methods access other properties on the same object. Its value depends on how the function is called,which you'll explore more in later sections.

Get an array of [key,value] pairs:
javascript


```
let user={ name: "Alice",age: 30 }

let entries=Object.entries(user)console.log(entries)// [["name","Alice"],["age",30]]

// Iterate with destructuring
for(let [key,value] of Object.entries(user)){
  console.log(key,value)}
// name Alice
// age 30

```

Loop over an object's keys:
javascript


```
let scores={ alice: 95,bob: 87,charlie: 92 }

for(let name in scores){
  console.log(name,scores[name])}
// alice 95
// bob 87
// charlie 92

```

Use  `for...in`  for objects. For arrays,prefer  `for...of`  or array methods.  `for...in`  on arrays iterates indices as strings and includes inherited properties.

Copy properties from one object to another:
javascript


```
let defaults={ color: "blue",size: "medium" }
let options={ size: "large" }

let merged=Object.assign({},defaults,options)console.log(merged)// { color: "blue",size: "large" }

```

Later sources override earlier ones. The first argument is the target(use  `{}`  for a new object).  `Object.assign`  modifies and returns the target.

Spread is often cleaner than  `Object.assign` :
javascript


```
let defaults={ color: "blue",size: "medium" }
let options={ size: "large" }

let merged={ ...defaults,...options }
console.log(merged)// { color: "blue",size: "large" }

// Add/override specific properties
let updated={ ...merged,color: "red",newProp: true }

```

Later spreads override earlier ones. Order matters.

Destructure nested objects:
javascript


```
let user={
  name: "Alice",address: {
    city: "Seattle",zip: "98101"
  }
}

let { address: { city } }=user
console.log(city)// "Seattle"

// With renaming
let { address: { city: userCity } }=user
console.log(userCity)// "Seattle"

```

Nested destructuring can get complex. For deep nesting,consider extracting step by step.

Spread and  `Object.assign()`  create shallow copies. They copy top-level properties,but nested objects remain as references.
javascript


```
const orig={ a: 1,nested: { b: 2 } };
const copy={ ...orig };
copy.nested.b=99;
console.log(orig.nested.b); // 99!

```

For plain objects,shallow copies work fine. For nested objects,you need deep cloning techniques.

Practice object operations:
javascript


```
let product={
  name: "Laptop",price: 999,specs: {
    ram: "16GB",storage: "512GB"
  }
}

// Access nested property
console.log(product.specs.ram)// "16GB"

// Add a property
product.inStock=true

// Destructure
let { name,price }=product
console.log(`${name}: $${price}`)// "Laptop: $999"

```

Practice with Object methods:
javascript


```
let inventory={
  apples: 50,bananas: 30,oranges: 45
}

// All keys
console.log(Object.keys(inventory))// ["apples","bananas","oranges"]

// Total count
let total=Object.values(inventory).reduce((a,b)=> a+b,0)console.log(total)// 125

// Transform to array of objects
let items=Object.entries(inventory).map(([name,qty])=>({ name,qty }))console.log(items)
```

Practice merging and updating:
javascript


```
let defaults={
  theme: "light",fontSize: 14,notifications: true
}

let userPrefs={
  theme: "dark",fontSize: 16
}

// Merge with user preferences taking priority
let settings={ ...defaults,...userPrefs }
console.log(settings)// { theme: "dark",fontSize: 16,notifications: true }

// Update single property
let updated={ ...settings,notifications: false }

```

Build a user profile system:
javascript


```
function createUser(name,email){
  return {
    id: Date.now(),name,email,createdAt: new Date(),settings: { theme: "light",notifications: true }
  }
}

function updateSettings(user,newSettings){
  return {
    ...user,settings: { ...user.settings,...newSettings }
  }
}

let user=createUser("Alice","alice@example.com")user=updateSettings(user,{ theme: "dark" })
```

An array of objects stores a collection of similar items. Each object has the same structure but different values.
javascript


```
const users=[
  { name: "Alice",age: 25 },{ name: "Bob",age: 30 }
];
console.log(users[0].name); // "Alice"

```

Access works in two steps: bracket notation for the array index,then dot notation for the property.

You can build arrays of objects incrementally using  `push()` . This pattern appears when collecting user input or API responses.
javascript


```
const products=[];
products.push({ name: "Laptop",price: 999 });
products.push({ name: "Mouse",price: 29 });
console.log(products.length); // 2

```

Each push adds one object to your collection.

Objects often contain arrays as property values. A user might have an array of orders. A post might have an array of comments.
javascript


```
const user={
  name: "Alice",orders: [101,102,103]
};
console.log(user.orders.length); // 3

```

You access the array with dot notation,then use any array method on it.

Use  `for...of`  or  `forEach`  to process each object in an array. The loop variable holds one complete object per iteration.
javascript


```
const users=[
  { name: "Alice" },{ name: "Bob" }
];
for(const user of users){
  console.log(user.name);
}

```

Inside the loop,`user`  is a full object. You can access any of its properties.

The  `find()`  method locates the first object matching a condition. It returns the object itself,not its index.
javascript


```
const users=[
  { id: 1,name: "Alice" },{ id: 2,name: "Bob" }
];
const found=users.find(u=> u.id===2);
console.log(found.name); // "Bob"

```

If no match exists,`find()`  returns  `undefined` .

The  `filter()`  method returns all objects matching a condition,not just the first. You get a new array containing only matches.
javascript


```
const products=[
  { name: "A",price: 10 },{ name: "B",price: 50 },{ name: "C",price: 25 }
];
const cheap=products.filter(p=> p.price < 30);
// [{ name: "A",price: 10 },{ name: "C",price: 25 }]

```

The  `map()`  method creates a new array by transforming each object. Use it to extract specific properties or reshape data.
javascript


```
const users=[
  { name: "Alice",age: 25 },{ name: "Bob",age: 30 }
];
const names=users.map(u=> u.name);
// ["Alice","Bob"]

```

You transformed an array of objects into an array of strings.

Map can return new objects with different structures. This reshapes your data without modifying the originals.
javascript


```
const users=[
  { firstName: "Alice",lastName: "Smith" }
];
const formatted=users.map(u=>({
  fullName: u.firstName+" "+u.lastName
}));
// [{ fullName: "Alice Smith" }]

```

Note the parentheses around the object literal to avoid syntax ambiguity.

The  `sort()`  method needs a compare function for objects. Return negative to sort a before b,positive for b before a.
javascript


```
const users=[
  { name: "Bob",age: 30 },{ name: "Alice",age: 25 }
];
users.sort((a,b)=> a.age - b.age);
// Alice(25)comes before Bob(30)
```

This sorts by age ascending. Use  `b.age - a.age`  for descending.

For string properties,use  `localeCompare()`  instead of subtraction. This handles alphabetical order correctly.
javascript


```
const users=[
  { name: "Bob" },{ name: "Alice" }
];
users.sort((a,b)=> a.name.localeCompare(b.name));
// Alice,Bob

```

 `localeCompare`  returns negative,zero,or positive,which  `sort()`  needs.

The  `reduce()`  method can calculate totals from object properties. Set an initial value and accumulate from each object.
javascript


```
const items=[
  { price: 10 },{ price: 20 },{ price: 15 }
];
const total=items.reduce((sum,item)=> sum+item.price,0);
console.log(total); // 45

```

This sums all prices into a single number.

Use  `reduce()`  to group objects by a property value. The accumulator builds an object where keys are categories.
javascript


```
const items=[
  { type: "fruit",name: "apple" },{ type: "veggie",name: "carrot" },{ type: "fruit",name: "banana" }
];
const grouped=items.reduce((acc,item)=> {
  acc[item.type]=acc[item.type] || [];
  acc[item.type].push(item);
  return acc;
},{});

```

Objects can contain other objects as property values. This creates hierarchical data structures.
javascript


```
const company={
  name: "TechCorp",address: {
    city: "Seattle",zip: "98101"
  }
};
console.log(company.address.city); // "Seattle"

```

Chain dot notation to access nested properties. Each dot drills one level deeper.

Real API data often has multiple nesting levels. Work through step by step,checking each level exists.
javascript


```
const response={
  data: {
    user: {
      profile: {
        name: "Alice"
      }
    }
  }
};
const name=response.data.user.profile.name;

```

If any level is missing,you'll get an error. We'll learn safe access patterns soon.

The spread operator(`...`)copies object properties into a new object. Use it to clone or merge objects.
javascript


```
const original={ a: 1,b: 2 };
const copy={ ...original };
const extended={ ...original,c: 3 };
// { a: 1,b: 2,c: 3 }

```

Later properties override earlier ones if keys match.

Spread multiple objects to merge them. Properties from later objects override earlier ones.
javascript


```
const defaults={ theme: "light",lang: "en" };
const userPrefs={ theme: "dark" };
const settings={ ...defaults,...userPrefs };
// { theme: "dark",lang: "en" }

```

This pattern is common for applying user settings over defaults.

Spreading an array of objects creates a new array,but the objects inside are still references.
javascript


```
const original=[{ id: 1 }];
const copy=[...original];
copy[0].id=99;
console.log(original[0].id); // 99!

```

This is a shallow copy. For independent copies,you need to clone each object too.

Destructuring can reach into nested structures. Match the structure you're extracting from.
javascript


```
const user={
  name: "Alice",address: { city: "Seattle" }
};
const { address: { city } }=user;
console.log(city); // "Seattle"

```

You can destructure as deeply as the data is nested.

Destructure objects directly in function parameters. This makes the function signature show what properties you need.
javascript


```
function greet({ name,age }){
  console.log(`${name} is ${age}`);
}
greet({ name: "Alice",age: 25 });
// "Alice is 25"

```

Callers see exactly which properties the function uses.

Provide default values in destructuring patterns. They apply when the property is undefined.
javascript


```
const { name,role="user" }={ name: "Alice" };
console.log(role); // "user"

function config({ timeout=1000 }={}){
  console.log(timeout);
}

```

The  `={}`  handles when no object is passed at all.

Combine spread and destructuring to update objects without mutating them. This pattern is common in React and Redux.
javascript


```
const user={ name: "Alice",age: 25 };
const updated={ ...user,age: 26 };
// user unchanged,updated has new age

```

The original remains intact. You create a new object with your changes.

For nested updates without mutation,spread at each level you need to change.
javascript


```
const user={
  name: "Alice",address: { city: "Seattle",zip: "98101" }
};
const updated={
  ...user,address: { ...user.address,city: "Portland" }
};

```

Spread the outer object,then spread and update the nested one.

JSON is the standard format for data exchange.  `JSON.parse()`  converts JSON strings to objects.  `JSON.stringify()`  converts objects to JSON.
javascript


```
const json='{"name":"Alice"}';
const obj=JSON.parse(json);
console.log(obj.name); // "Alice"

const str=JSON.stringify(obj);
// '{"name":"Alice"}'

```

A quick way to deep clone is stringify then parse. This creates completely independent copies of nested structures.
javascript


```
const original={ a: { b: 1 } };
const clone=JSON.parse(JSON.stringify(original));
clone.a.b=99;
console.log(original.a.b); // 1(unchanged)
```

Note: This doesn't work with functions,undefined,or circular references.

A shopping cart combines all these concepts. It's an array of product objects with methods to add,remove,and calculate totals.
javascript


```
const cart={
  items: [],addItem(product){
    this.items.push(product);
  },total(){
    return this.items.reduce((sum,item)=> sum+item.price * item.qty,0);
  }
};

```

API responses typically have metadata and nested data. You'll use optional chaining and destructuring to extract what you need.
javascript


```
const response={
  status: 200,data: {
    users: [{ id: 1,name: "Alice" }]
  }
};
const users=response?.data?.users ?? [];
const [firstUser]=users;

```

This safely handles missing data at any level.

The  `catch`  block receives the error object. You can inspect it to understand what went wrong and respond appropriately.
javascript


```
try {
  JSON.parse("invalid json");
} catch(error){
  console.log(error.name);    // "SyntaxError"
  console.log(error.message); // Parsing error details
}

```

The catch block only runs if an error occurs in the try block.

The  `finally`  block runs whether or not an error occurred. Use it for cleanup tasks like closing connections or releasing resources.
javascript


```
try {
  openFile();
  processFile();
} catch(error){
  logError(error);
} finally {
  closeFile(); // Always runs
}

```

Finally runs even if catch throws another error.

You can use  `try/finally`  without  `catch` . The error still propagates up,but your cleanup code runs first.
javascript


```
function process(){
  try {
    doWork();
  } finally {
    cleanup(); // Runs before error propagates
  }
}

```

This pattern ensures cleanup happens even when you want errors to bubble up.

The  `throw`  statement lets you create your own errors. When you detect a problem,throw an error to signal it to callers.
javascript


```
function divide(a,b){
  if(b===0){
    throw new Error("Cannot divide by zero");
  }
  return a / b;
}

```

Throw stops execution and transfers control to the nearest catch block.

Throw specific error types to give callers more information. Use built-in types or create custom ones.
javascript


```
function setAge(age){
  if(typeof age !=="number"){
    throw new TypeError("Age must be a number");
  }
  if(age < 0 || age > 150){
    throw new RangeError("Age must be 0-150");
  }
}

```

Specific types help callers handle different errors differently.

Sometimes you want to log an error but let it propagate. Catch it,do your work,then throw it again.
javascript


```
try {
  riskyOperation();
} catch(error){
  console.error("Error occurred:",error);
  throw error; // Rethrow for caller to handle
}

```

This pattern is common in middleware and logging layers.

Extend the Error class to create custom error types for your application. This helps callers handle specific error cases.
javascript


```
class ValidationError extends Error {
  constructor(message){
    super(message);
    this.name="ValidationError";
  }
}

throw new ValidationError("Email is invalid");

```

Custom errors make your API clearer and debugging easier.

Custom errors can carry additional information. Add properties for error codes,affected fields,or recovery hints.
javascript


```
class ApiError extends Error {
  constructor(message,statusCode){
    super(message);
    this.name="ApiError";
    this.statusCode=statusCode;
  }
}

throw new ApiError("Not found",404);

```

Extra properties help callers make better decisions.

Use  `instanceof`  to check error types and handle each appropriately.
javascript


```
try {
  processInput(data);
} catch(error){
  if(error instanceof ValidationError){
    showFieldError(error.field);
  } else if(error instanceof NetworkError){
    showRetryButton();
  } else {
    throw error; // Unknown error,rethrow
  }
}

```

Validate inputs before operations to prevent errors. Check types,ranges,and required fields early.
javascript


```
function processUser(user){
  if(!user)throw new Error("User required");
  if(!user.email)throw new Error("Email required");
  // Safe to proceed
}

```

Fail fast with clear messages rather than failing later with cryptic ones.

Optional chaining prevents TypeError when accessing nested properties that might not exist.
javascript


```
// Without optional chaining
if(user && user.address && user.address.city){}

// With optional chaining
if(user?.address?.city){}

```

Use  `?.`  to safely access objects without explicit null checks at each level.

Nullish coalescing provides defaults for null or undefined values without treating 0 or empty strings as missing.
javascript


```
const port=config.port ?? 3000;
const name=user.name ?? "Guest";

// Unlike ||,this preserves 0 and ""
const count=data.count ?? 10; // 0 stays 0

```

Good error messages explain what went wrong and how to fix it. Include the invalid value and expected format.
javascript


```
// Bad
throw new Error("Invalid input");

// Good
throw new Error(`Expected email format,got: ${input}`);

```

Messages should help developers debug without exposing sensitive data.

Log errors with context to help debugging. Include timestamps,user IDs,and operation details.
javascript


```
catch(error){
  console.error({
    message: error.message,stack: error.stack,userId: currentUser.id,operation: "checkout",timestamp: new Date().toISOString()});
}

```

In production,send logs to a monitoring service.

Set up global handlers to catch errors that slip through. In browsers,use  `window.onerror` . In Node.js,use  `process.on('uncaughtException')` .
javascript


```
window.onerror=function(msg,url,line){
  logToServer({ msg,url,line });
  return true; // Prevent default handling
};

```

Global handlers are a safety net,not a replacement for proper handling.

Unhandled promise rejections need their own handler. These occur when you forget to catch async errors.
javascript


```
window.onunhandledrejection=function(event){
  console.error("Unhandled:",event.reason);
  event.preventDefault();
};

```

In Node.js,use  `process.on('unhandledRejection')` . We'll cover async errors more in the next section.

Wrap independent features in separate try/catch blocks. If one feature fails,others keep working.
javascript


```
function initApp(){
  try { initAnalytics(); } 
  catch(e){ console.warn("Analytics failed"); }

  try { initChat(); } 
  catch(e){ console.warn("Chat failed"); }

  // Core features
  initAuth();
  initUI();
}

```

Non-critical failures shouldn't break critical features.

Test that your error handling works correctly. Trigger errors intentionally and verify the response.
javascript


```
// Test that validation throws
expect(()=> setAge(-1)).toThrow(RangeError);

// Test error message
expect(()=> setAge("old")).toThrow("Age must be a number");

```

Error paths need testing just like success paths.

Avoid these common mistakes:

Empty catch blocks that hide errors
Catching errors too broadly
Not logging enough context
Swallowing errors in callbacks

javascript


```
// Never do this
try { riskyCode(); } catch(e){}

// At minimum,log it
try { riskyCode(); } catch(e){ console.error(e); }

```

`setTimeout`  runs code once after a delay.  `setInterval`  runs code repeatedly at an interval.
javascript


```
setTimeout(()=> {
  console.log("After 1 second");
},1000);

const id=setInterval(()=> {
  console.log("Every 2 seconds");
},2000);

clearInterval(id); // Stop the interval

```

Delays are in milliseconds. 1000 ms=1 second.

Even  `setTimeout(fn,0)`  doesn't run immediately. It schedules the callback for the next event loop iteration.
javascript


```
console.log("First");
setTimeout(()=> console.log("Third"),0);
console.log("Second");
// Output: First,Second,Third

```

This defers work until after current synchronous code completes.

Callbacks are functions passed to async operations. They run when the operation completes,receiving the result.
javascript


```
function fetchUser(id,callback){
  // Simulated async operation
  setTimeout(()=> {
    callback({ id,name: "Alice" });
  },100);
}

fetchUser(1,(user)=> {
  console.log(user.name); // "Alice"
});

```

Node.js uses error-first callbacks. The first parameter is an error(or null if success). The second is the result.
javascript


```
readFile("data.txt",(err,data)=> {
  if(err){
    console.error("Failed:",err);
    return;
  }
  console.log(data);
});

```

Always check the error parameter first before using the result.

When async operations depend on each other,callbacks nest deeply. This creates "callback hell" or the "pyramid of doom."
javascript


```
getUser(id,(user)=> {
  getOrders(user.id,(orders)=> {
    getOrderDetails(orders[0].id,(details)=> {
      // Deeply nested,hard to read
    });
  });
});

```

This code is hard to read,maintain,and debug. Promises solve this.

A Promise represents a future value. It's either pending(waiting),fulfilled(success),or rejected(failed).
javascript


```
const promise=fetchData();

promise.then((data)=> {
  console.log("Success:",data);
});

promise.catch((error)=> {
  console.log("Failed:",error);
});

```

Promises flatten callback hell into a chain of  `.then()`  calls.

Create a Promise with the  `new Promise()`  constructor. It takes a function with  `resolve`  and  `reject`  parameters.
javascript


```
const wait=new Promise((resolve,reject)=> {
  setTimeout(()=> {
    resolve("Done!");
  },1000);
});

wait.then(result=> console.log(result));

```

Call  `resolve(value)`  on success,`reject(error)`  on failure.

The  `.then()`  method takes a callback that runs when the promise fulfills. It receives the resolved value.
javascript


```
fetchUser(1).then(user=> {
    console.log(user.name);
    return user.id;
  }).then(id=> {
    console.log("ID:",id);
  });

```

 `.then()`  returns a new promise,enabling chaining.

The  `.catch()`  method handles errors. It catches rejections from anywhere in the chain above it.
javascript


```
fetchData().then(process).then(save).catch(error=> {
    console.error("Something failed:",error);
  });

```

One  `.catch()`  at the end handles errors from any step.

The  `.finally()`  method runs whether the promise fulfills or rejects. Use it for cleanup that should happen either way.
javascript


```
showSpinner();

fetchData().then(displayData).catch(showError).finally(()=> {
    hideSpinner(); // Always runs
  });

```

 `.finally()`  doesn't receive any arguments.

Create immediately settled promises with static methods:
javascript


```
// Immediately fulfilled
Promise.resolve(42).then(x=> console.log(x));

// Immediately rejected
Promise.reject(new Error("Failed")).catch(e=> console.log(e.message));

```

Useful for returning consistent promise-based APIs.

`Promise.all()`  runs multiple promises in parallel and waits for all to complete. It returns an array of results.
javascript


```
Promise.all([
  fetchUser(1),fetchUser(2),fetchUser(3)]).then(users=> {
  console.log(users); // [user1,user2,user3]
});

```

If any promise rejects,`Promise.all`  rejects immediately.

`Promise.race()`  returns the first promise to settle,whether it fulfills or rejects.
javascript


```
Promise.race([
  fetchFromServer1(),fetchFromServer2()]).then(result=> {
  // First response wins
});

```

Useful for timeouts: race your operation against a timeout promise.

`Promise.allSettled()`  waits for all promises to settle. It never rejects. You get the status and value/reason for each.
javascript


```
Promise.allSettled([p1,p2,p3]).then(results=> {
    results.forEach(r=> {
      if(r.status==="fulfilled"){
        console.log(r.value);
      } else {
        console.log(r.reason);
      }
    });
  });

```

The  `async`  keyword marks a function as asynchronous. Async functions always return a promise.
javascript


```
async function getData(){
  return "Hello";
}

getData().then(console.log); // "Hello"

```

Inside async functions,you can use  `await`  to pause for promises.

`await`  pauses execution until a promise settles. It returns the resolved value directly.
javascript


```
async function getUser(){
  const response=await fetch("/api/user");
  const user=await response.json();
  return user;
}

```

 `await`  can only be used inside  `async`  functions.

Async/await makes async code read like synchronous code. Compare:
javascript


```
// With .then()getUser(1).then(user=> getOrders(user.id)).then(orders=> console.log(orders));

// With async/await
const user=await getUser(1);
const orders=await getOrders(user.id);
console.log(orders);

```

Both do the same thing. Async/await is often more readable.

Use try/catch to handle errors in async functions. Rejected promises throw when awaited.
javascript


```
async function loadData(){
  try {
    const data=await fetchData();
    return process(data);
  } catch(error){
    console.error("Failed:",error);
    return null;
  }
}

```

This feels more natural than  `.catch()`  chains.

Sequential awaits run one at a time. For parallel execution,start all promises first,then await them.
javascript


```
// Sequential(slow)const a=await fetchA();
const b=await fetchB();

// Parallel(fast)const [a,b]=await Promise.all([
  fetchA(),fetchB()]);

```

Use  `Promise.all`  when operations don't depend on each other.

Common mistakes with async code:

Forgetting  `await`(you get a promise,not the value)Using  `await`  outside async functions
Sequential awaits when parallel works
Not catching errors

javascript


```
// Wrong: forEach doesn't wait
arr.forEach(async(x)=> await process(x));

// Right: use for...of
for(const x of arr)await process(x);

```

In ES modules,you can use  `await`  at the top level without wrapping in an async function.
javascript


```
// In a .mjs file or type="module"
const config=await loadConfig();
const db=await connectDB(config);

export { db };

```

The module waits for setup before exporting.

The  `fetch()`  function makes HTTP requests and returns a promise. It's the modern way to load data from servers.
javascript


```
const response=await fetch("/api/users");
const users=await response.json();
console.log(users);

```

 `fetch`  returns a Response object. Call  `.json()`  to parse JSON data.

`fetch`  only rejects on network errors,not HTTP errors like 404 or 500. Check  `response.ok`  for success.
javascript


```
const response=await fetch(url);

if(!response.ok){
  throw new Error(`HTTP ${response.status}`);
}

const data=await response.json();

```

Always check the response status before parsing the body.

Use  `for await...of`  to iterate over async data sources like streams or paginated APIs.
javascript


```
async function* generateIds(){
  yield await fetchId(1);
  yield await fetchId(2);
}

for await(const id of generateIds()){
  console.log(id);
}

```

This processes data as it arrives,without loading everything at once.

Debouncing waits for a pause in events before acting. Throttling limits how often an action can occur.
javascript


```
// Debounce: wait 300ms after last keystroke
let timeout;
input.oninput=()=> {
  clearTimeout(timeout);
  timeout=setTimeout(search,300);
};

```

Use debouncing for search inputs. Use throttling for scroll handlers.

Named exports let you export multiple values from a module. Each export has a name that importers must match.
javascript


```
// utils.js
export const PI=3.14159;
export function double(x){ return x * 2; }
export class Calculator {}

```

You can export variables,functions,and classes by name.

Each module can have one default export. It's the main thing the module provides.
javascript


```
// User.js
export default class User {
  constructor(name){
    this.name=name;
  }
}

```

Default exports are common for modules that export a single class or function.

A module can have both default and named exports. Import them together in one statement.
javascript


```
// api.js
export default function request(){}
export const GET="GET";
export const POST="POST";

// app.js
import request,{ GET,POST } from "./api.js";

```

Default comes first without braces,then named in braces.

Import all exports as a single namespace object with  `* as` . Access exports as properties.
javascript


```
import * as math from "./math.js";

console.log(math.add(1,2));
console.log(math.subtract(5,3));
console.log(math.PI);

```

This is useful when you need many exports from one module.

Re-export from other modules to create a single entry point. This is common for library index files.
javascript


```
// index.js
export { add,subtract } from "./math.js";
export { format } from "./string.js";
export { default as User } from "./User.js";

```

Consumers import from index.js instead of individual files.

Use  `import()`  as a function for dynamic imports. It returns a promise that resolves to the module.
javascript


```
button.onclick=async()=> {
  const { heavy }=await import("./heavy.js");
  heavy();
};

```

Dynamic imports enable code splitting. Load modules only when needed.

Dynamic imports work inside conditions. This lets you load different modules based on environment or user actions.
javascript


```
const mod=await import(isDev ? "./dev-tools.js" : "./prod-tools.js");

if(userWantsFeature){
  const { feature }=await import("./feature.js");
  feature();
}

```

Variables in a module are private unless exported. This prevents pollution of the global scope.
javascript


```
// utils.js
const secret="hidden"; // Private
export const visible="public"; // Accessible

// app.js
import { visible } from "./utils.js";
// secret is not accessible

```

In Node.js,use  `.mjs`  extension or set  `"type": "module"`  in package.json to use ES modules.
json


```
// package.json
{
  "type": "module"
}

```

With this setting,`.js`  files are treated as ES modules. Without it,use  `.mjs`  extension explicitly.

CommonJS(CJS)is Node.js's original module system. You'll encounter it in older code.
javascript


```
// Exporting
module.exports={ add,subtract };
// or
exports.add=add;

// Importing
const { add }=require("./math");

```

CJS is synchronous and mainly used server-side.

Circular dependencies occur when modules import each other. ES modules handle this gracefully,but it can cause issues.
javascript


```
// a.js
import { b } from "./b.js";
export const a="A"+b;

// b.js
import { a } from "./a.js";
export const b="B"+a;

```

Avoid circular dependencies by restructuring code or using a third module.

A barrel file(usually index.js)re-exports from multiple modules. It creates a clean public API.
javascript


```
// components/index.js
export { Button } from "./Button.js";
export { Input } from "./Input.js";
export { Modal } from "./Modal.js";

// Usage
import { Button,Input } from "./components";

```

Import maps let you control how module specifiers resolve in browsers.
html


```
<script type="importmap">
{
  "imports": {
    "lodash": "/node_modules/lodash-es/lodash.js","@/": "/src/"
  }
}
</script>

<script type="module">
import _ from "lodash";
import { api } from "@/services/api.js";
</script>

```

A class is a blueprint for creating objects. It defines what properties and methods objects of that type will have.
javascript


```
class Car {
  // Blueprint for car objects
}

const myCar=new Car(); // Create from blueprint
const yourCar=new Car();

```

Each object created from a class is called an instance.

Declare classes with the  `class`  keyword. By convention,class names use PascalCase.
javascript


```
class User {
  constructor(name){
    this.name=name;
  }

  greet(){
    return `Hello,${this.name}`;
  }
}

```

The constructor runs when you create an instance. Methods are functions that operate on the instance.

The  `constructor`  method initializes new instances. It receives arguments passed to  `new`  and sets up instance properties.
javascript


```
class Rectangle {
  constructor(width,height){
    this.width=width;
    this.height=height;
  }
}

const rect=new Rectangle(10,5);
console.log(rect.width); // 10

```

Inside methods,`this`  refers to the instance the method was called on.
javascript


```
class User {
  constructor(name){
    this.name=name;
  }

  sayHi(){
    console.log(`Hi,I'm ${this.name}`);
  }
}

const alice=new User("Alice");
alice.sayHi(); // "Hi,I'm Alice"

```

Each instance has its own  `this`  context.

Class fields let you declare properties without the constructor. They're initialized for each instance.
javascript


```
class Task {
  status="pending"; // Class field

  complete(){
    this.status="done";
  }
}

const task=new Task();
console.log(task.status); // "pending"

```

Fields can have default values.

Prefix field names with  `#`  to make them private. Private fields can only be accessed inside the class.
javascript


```
class BankAccount {
  #balance=0;

  deposit(amount){
    this.#balance+=amount;
  }

  getBalance(){
    return this.#balance;
  }
}

```

Outside code cannot access  `#balance`  directly.

Methods can also be private. Use  `#`  prefix to hide implementation details.
javascript


```
class Validator {
  #sanitize(input){
    return input.trim().toLowerCase();
  }

  validate(email){
    const clean=this.#sanitize(email);
    return clean.includes("@");
  }
}

```

 `#sanitize`  is internal. Only  `validate`  is public.

Getters let you define computed properties. They look like properties but run code when accessed.
javascript


```
class Rectangle {
  constructor(w,h){
    this.width=w;
    this.height=h;
  }

  get area(){
    return this.width * this.height;
  }
}

const r=new Rectangle(4,5);
console.log(r.area); // 20(no parentheses)
```

Setters run code when you assign to a property. Use them for validation or side effects.
javascript


```
class User {
  #age=0;

  set age(value){
    if(value < 0)throw new Error("Invalid age");
    this.#age=value;
  }

  get age(){
    return this.#age;
  }
}

```

Setters and getters often pair together.

Static methods belong to the class,not instances. Call them on the class directly.
javascript


```
class MathUtils {
  static square(x){
    return x * x;
  }
}

console.log(MathUtils.square(5)); // 25
// Not: new MathUtils().square(5)
```

Static methods are useful for utility functions.

Static fields store data shared across all instances. Use them for constants or instance counters.
javascript


```
class User {
  static count=0;

  constructor(name){
    this.name=name;
    User.count++;
  }
}

new User("Alice");
new User("Bob");
console.log(User.count); // 2

```

Use  `extends`  to create a subclass that inherits from a parent class.
javascript


```
class Animal {
  speak(){
    console.log("Some sound");
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  speak(){
    console.log("Woof!");
  }
}

const dog=new Dog();
dog.speak(); // "Woof!"

```

The subclass inherits methods and can override them.

Use  `super`  to call the parent class constructor or methods.
javascript


```
class Animal {
  constructor(name){
    this.name=name;
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  constructor(name,breed){
    super(name); // Call parent constructor
    this.breed=breed;
  }
}

```

In subclass constructors,call  `super()`  before using  `this` .

Call parent methods with  `super.methodName()`  to extend rather than replace behavior.
javascript


```
class Animal {
  describe(){
    return `Name: ${this.name}`;
  }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
  describe(){
    return super.describe()+`,Breed: ${this.breed}`;
  }
}

```

This lets you add to parent behavior instead of replacing it entirely.

Subclasses can override parent methods by defining methods with the same name.
javascript


```
class Shape {
  area(){
    return 0;
  }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
  constructor(radius){
    super();
    this.radius=radius;
  }

  area(){
    return Math.PI * this.radius ** 2;
  }
}

```

Polymorphism lets you treat different classes uniformly if they share methods.
javascript


```
class Circle { area(){ /*...*/ } }
class Square { area(){ /*...*/ } }

function totalArea(shapes){
  return shapes.reduce((sum,s)=> sum+s.area(),0);
}

// Works with any shape that has area()totalArea([new Circle(5),new Square(4)]);

```

Composition builds objects from smaller pieces rather than inheriting from parent classes.
javascript


```
// Composition
const canSwim={
  swim(){ console.log("Swimming"); }
};

const canFly={
  fly(){ console.log("Flying"); }
};

const duck={ ...canSwim,...canFly };
duck.swim(); // Works!
duck.fly();  // Works!

```

Composition is often more flexible than deep inheritance.

Mixins add functionality to classes without inheritance. Copy methods from helper objects.
javascript


```
const TimestampMixin={
  getCreatedAt(){
    return this.createdAt;
  }
};

class User {
  constructor(){
    this.createdAt=new Date();
  }
}

Object.assign(User.prototype,TimestampMixin);

```

Mixins help share code across unrelated classes.

JavaScript doesn't have abstract classes,but you can throw errors for methods that must be implemented.
javascript


```
class Shape {
  area(){
    throw new Error("Subclass must implement area()");
  }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
  area(){
    return Math.PI * this.radius ** 2;
  }
}

```

This pattern ensures subclasses provide required methods.

Factory functions create objects without the  `class`  keyword. They return new objects with closures for privacy.
javascript


```
function createCounter(){
  let count=0; // Private via closure

  return {
    increment(){ count++; },getCount(){ return count; }
  };
}

const counter=createCounter();

```

Some prefer factories over classes for their flexibility.

`querySelector()`  finds the first element matching a CSS selector. It's flexible and widely used.
javascript


```
const el=document.querySelector(".item");
const nested=document.querySelector("div > p.intro");
const byId=document.querySelector("#header");

```

Any valid CSS selector works. Returns  `null`  if no match.

Set  `textContent`  or  `innerHTML`  to change element content.
javascript


```
const el=document.querySelector("#message");
el.textContent="Updated text";
el.innerHTML="<strong>Bold text</strong>";

```

Setting  `innerHTML`  parses the string as HTML. Be careful with user input to avoid XSS attacks.

The  `classList`  property provides methods to add,remove,and toggle CSS classes.
javascript


```
const el=document.querySelector("div");
el.classList.add("active");
el.classList.remove("hidden");
el.classList.toggle("highlight");
el.classList.contains("active"); // true

```

This is cleaner than manipulating the  `className`  string directly.

The  `style`  property lets you set inline CSS styles. Property names use camelCase.
javascript


```
const el=document.querySelector("div");
el.style.backgroundColor="blue";
el.style.fontSize="20px";
el.style.display="none";

```

For multiple styles,prefer adding CSS classes instead of inline styles.

Use  `getComputedStyle()`  to read the actual styles applied to an element,including styles from CSS files.
javascript


```
const el=document.querySelector("div");
const styles=getComputedStyle(el);
console.log(styles.backgroundColor);
console.log(styles.fontSize);

```

This returns the final computed values after all CSS rules apply.

Use  `document.createElement()`  to create new elements. The element exists in memory until you add it to the DOM.
javascript


```
const div=document.createElement("div");
div.textContent="New content";
div.classList.add("card");
// Element exists but isn't visible yet

```

Set properties and content before inserting for better performance.

Add elements to the DOM with  `appendChild()`  or  `append()` .
javascript


```
const parent=document.querySelector("#container");
const child=document.createElement("p");
child.textContent="Hello";

parent.appendChild(child);
// or
parent.append(child,"text",anotherElement);

```

 `append()`  accepts multiple arguments and text strings.

Remove elements with  `remove()`  or  `removeChild()` .
javascript


```
const el=document.querySelector(".delete-me");
el.remove(); // Modern way

// Or through parent
const parent=el.parentNode;
parent.removeChild(el);

```

 `remove()`  is simpler and works in all modern browsers.

A DocumentFragment is a lightweight container for building DOM structures before inserting them.
javascript


```
const fragment=document.createDocumentFragment();

for(let i=0; i < 100; i++){
  const li=document.createElement("li");
  li.textContent=`Item ${i}`;
  fragment.appendChild(li);
}

list.appendChild(fragment); // One DOM update

```

This is faster than inserting elements one by one.

DOM manipulation fails if elements don't exist yet. Wait for the DOM to load:
javascript


```
document.addEventListener("DOMContentLoaded",()=> {
  // DOM is ready,elements exist
  const el=document.querySelector("#app");
});

```

Or place scripts at the end of  `<body>`,or use  `defer`  attribute on script tags.

Use  `addEventListener()`  to run code when an event occurs on an element.
javascript


```
const button=document.querySelector("button");

button.addEventListener("click",function(){
  console.log("Button clicked!");
});

```

The first argument is the event type. The second is the handler function that runs when the event fires.

Event handlers receive an event object with details about what happened.
javascript


```
button.addEventListener("click",function(event){
  console.log(event.type);   // "click"
  console.log(event.target); // The clicked element
  console.log(event.clientX); // Mouse X position
});

```

The event object varies by event type but always includes  `type`  and  `target` .

The  `event.target`  property tells you which element triggered the event.
javascript


```
list.addEventListener("click",function(event){
  console.log(event.target);       // Element clicked
  console.log(event.currentTarget); // Element with handler
});

```

 `target`  is the actual element clicked.  `currentTarget`  is where the handler is attached.

Some events have default behaviors. Links redirect,forms submit,keys type. Use  `preventDefault()`  to stop these.
javascript


```
form.addEventListener("submit",function(event){
  event.preventDefault(); // Don't submit normally
  // Handle form data with JavaScript
});

link.addEventListener("click",function(event){
  event.preventDefault(); // Don't redirect
});

```

Mouse events track movement and button state:
javascript


```
el.addEventListener("mouseenter",()=> {
  el.classList.add("hovered");
});

el.addEventListener("mouseleave",()=> {
  el.classList.remove("hovered");
});

el.addEventListener("mousemove",(e)=> {
  console.log(e.clientX,e.clientY);
});

```

Use  `mouseenter` / `mouseleave`  over  `mouseover` / `mouseout`  to avoid bubbling issues.

Keyboard events fire when users press keys.  `keydown`  fires when pressed,`keyup`  when released.
javascript


```
input.addEventListener("keydown",(e)=> {
  console.log(e.key);  // "a","Enter","Escape"
  console.log(e.code); // "KeyA","Enter","Escape"

  if(e.key==="Enter"){
    submitForm();
  }
});

```

Use  `e.key`  for the character,`e.code`  for the physical key.

Forms have specific events for user input:
javascript


```
form.addEventListener("submit",handleSubmit);

input.addEventListener("input",(e)=> {
  // Fires on every change
  console.log(e.target.value);
});

input.addEventListener("change",(e)=> {
  // Fires when field loses focus
});

```

 `input`  fires on every keystroke. For text fields,`change`  fires when the user leaves the field. For checkboxes,radios,and selects,`change`  fires right away.

`focus`  fires when an element gains focus.  `blur`  fires when it loses focus.
javascript


```
input.addEventListener("focus",()=> {
  input.classList.add("active");
});

input.addEventListener("blur",()=> {
  input.classList.remove("active");
  validateField(input);
});

```

Use these for form validation and visual feedback.

When an event fires,it bubbles up through parent elements. A click on a button also fires on its parent div,and so on.
javascript


```
// Click on button bubbles to div
div.addEventListener("click",()=> {
  console.log("div clicked");
});

button.addEventListener("click",()=> {
  console.log("button clicked");
});
// Click button: logs both

```

Use  `stopPropagation()`  to prevent an event from bubbling to parent elements.
javascript


```
button.addEventListener("click",(e)=> {
  e.stopPropagation(); // Parent won't see this
  handleButtonClick();
});

modal.addEventListener("click",(e)=> {
  e.stopPropagation(); // Clicks inside modal don't close it
});

```

Events also have a capture phase going down before bubbling up. Enable capture with the third argument.
javascript


```
parent.addEventListener("click",handler,true);
// or
parent.addEventListener("click",handler,{
  capture: true
});

```

Capturing runs handlers top-down before the event reaches the target.

Instead of adding listeners to many children,add one to the parent and check  `event.target` .
javascript


```
ul.addEventListener("click",(e)=> {
  if(e.target.tagName==="LI"){
    e.target.classList.toggle("selected");
  }
});

```

This is more efficient and works for dynamically added elements.

Use  `closest()`  to find the nearest ancestor matching a selector. This handles clicks on nested elements.
javascript


```
list.addEventListener("click",(e)=> {
  const item=e.target.closest(".item");
  if(item){
    handleItemClick(item);
  }
});

```

This works even if you click on an icon inside the item.

Remove listeners with  `removeEventListener()` . You must pass the same function reference.
javascript


```
function handleClick(){ }

button.addEventListener("click",handleClick);
// Later...
button.removeEventListener("click",handleClick);

// This WON'T work:
button.addEventListener("click",()=> {});
button.removeEventListener("click",()=> {}); // Different function!

```

Use the  `once`  option to automatically remove a listener after it fires once.
javascript


```
button.addEventListener("click",handleClick,{
  once: true
});
// Handler runs once,then is automatically removed

```

Perfect for one-time setup actions or first-interaction handling.

Passive listeners promise not to call  `preventDefault()` . This improves scroll performance.
javascript


```
window.addEventListener("scroll",handleScroll,{
  passive: true
});

document.addEventListener("touchmove",handleTouch,{
  passive: true
});

```

Use passive for scroll and touch events when you don't need to prevent default behavior.

Create custom events for component communication:
javascript


```
// Create and dispatch
const event=new CustomEvent("userLogin",{
  detail: { userId: 123 }
});
element.dispatchEvent(event);

// Listen
element.addEventListener("userLogin",(e)=> {
  console.log(e.detail.userId);
});

```

Custom events let components communicate without tight coupling.

Debouncing delays handler execution until events stop firing. Use for search inputs.
javascript


```
let timeout;
input.addEventListener("input",(e)=> {
  clearTimeout(timeout);
  timeout=setTimeout(()=> {
    search(e.target.value);
  },300);
});

```

This waits 300ms after the user stops typing before searching.

Throttling ensures a handler runs at most once per time period. Use for scroll or resize.
javascript


```
let lastRun=0;
window.addEventListener("scroll",()=> {
  if(Date.now()- lastRun > 100){
    lastRun=Date.now();
    handleScroll();
  }
});

```

This runs at most every 100ms,no matter how often scroll fires.

Touch events handle finger interactions on mobile devices:
javascript


```
el.addEventListener("touchstart",handleStart);
el.addEventListener("touchmove",handleMove);
el.addEventListener("touchend",handleEnd);

```

For basic interactions,`click`  works on mobile too. Use touch events for gestures like swipe.

