```
describe('Database tests',()=> {
  beforeEach(()=> {
    // Runs before each test
    resetDatabase();
  });

  afterAll(()=> {
    // Runs after all tests
    closeConnection();
  });
});

```

 `beforeEach` / `afterEach`  run per test.  `beforeAll` / `afterAll`  run once per describe block.

Test async functions with  `async/await` :
javascript


```
test('fetches user data',async()=> {
  const user=await fetchUser(1);
  expect(user.name).toBe('Alice');
});

```

Jest waits for the promise to resolve. If it rejects,the test fails.

Test that async functions reject correctly:
javascript


```
test('rejects for invalid user',async()=> {
  await expect(fetchUser(-1)).rejects.toThrow('Invalid ID');
});

// Or with try/catch
test('rejects for invalid user',async()=> {
  try {
    await fetchUser(-1);
    throw new Error('Should have thrown');
  } catch(e){
    expect(e.message).toBe('Invalid ID');
  }
});

```

Mock functions track calls and control return values:
javascript


```
const mockFn=jest.fn();
mockFn('arg1','arg2');

expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalled();
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledWith('arg1','arg2');
expect(mockFn).toHaveBeenCalledTimes(1);

```

Mocks let you test code in isolation without real dependencies.

Mock entire modules to control their behavior:
javascript


```
jest.mock('./api');
import { fetchUser } from './api';

fetchUser.mockResolvedValue({ name: 'Test User' });

test('uses mocked API',async()=> {
  const user=await fetchUser(1);
  expect(user.name).toBe('Test User');
});

```

The real module never runs. Your test controls all responses.

Spies watch real functions without replacing them:
javascript


```
const spy=jest.spyOn(console,'log');

myFunction(); // calls console.log internally

expect(spy).toHaveBeenCalled();
expect(spy).toHaveBeenCalledWith('expected message');

spy.mockRestore(); // Restore original

```

Spies are useful when you want to verify calls but keep real behavior.

Jest provides a simulated DOM via jsdom:
javascript


```
test('button click updates text',()=> {
  document.body.innerHTML='<button id="btn">Click</button>';

  const btn=document.getElementById('btn');
  btn.addEventListener('click',()=> btn.textContent='Clicked');

  btn.click();

  expect(btn.textContent).toBe('Clicked');
});

```

Write code that can be tested:
javascript


```
// Hard to test(hidden dependency)function getPrice(){
  return fetchBasePrice()* 1.1;
}

// Testable(explicit dependency)function getPrice(basePrice){
  return basePrice * 1.1;
}

```

Pass dependencies as parameters. Avoid global state. Keep functions focused on one task.

Format console output for clarity:
javascript


```
// String substitution
console.log("User%s has%d items","Alice",5);

// Styled output
console.log("%cStyled text","color: blue; font-size: 20px");

// Object inspection
console.dir(element);
// In Node.js: console.dir(obj,{ depth: 2 })
```

Clear formatting helps when debugging complex data.

Add  `debugger;`  in your code to trigger a breakpoint:
javascript


```
function processData(data){
  debugger; // Pauses here when DevTools is open
  return data.map(transform);
}

```

This is useful when you want to pause at a specific point without clicking in DevTools. Remove debugger statements before production.

Right-click a line number to add a conditional breakpoint:
javascript


```
// Pause only when i===100
for(let i=0; i < 1000; i++){
  process(i); // Conditional breakpoint here
}

```

This avoids pausing 999 times to reach the iteration you care about.

Follow JavaScript naming conventions:
javascript


```
// Variables and functions: camelCase
const userName='Alice';
function getUserById(){}

// Classes: PascalCase
class UserAccount {}

// Constants: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE
const MAX_RETRY_COUNT=3;

```

Consistent naming makes code predictable.

Good comments explain why,not what:
javascript


```
// Bad: increments count
count++;

// Good: retry needed because API occasionally times out
count++;

```

Don't comment obvious code. Do explain complex logic,workarounds,and non-obvious decisions.

React uses components and JSX:
javascript


```
function Welcome({ name }){
  return <h1>Hello,{name}</h1>;
}

// Use it
<Welcome name="Alice" />

```

React's component model matches how you think about UIs. Learn React if you want maximum job opportunities.

Node.js runs JavaScript outside the browser. You can build APIs,servers,and command-line tools.
javascript


```
const http=require('http');
http.createServer((req,res)=> {
  res.end('Hello from Node!');
}).listen(3000);

```

Your JavaScript skills transfer directly to backend development.

Express is the most popular Node.js web framework:
javascript


```
const express=require('express');
const app=express();

app.get('/users',(req,res)=> {
  res.json([{ name: 'Alice' }]);
});

app.listen(3000);

```

Express handles routing,middleware,and request/response processing.
